+Furry makedonia It's not fake. When it comes to the media, don't believe 
the lies they tell you regarding the Isis' beheading videos being fake.
It's not fake. First of all, most times when filming anything professional 
such as this Isis' video since it was televised, video directors have to 
use mirror reflectors outside to draw sun light onto the person's face or 
else, the audience who watches the video wont be able to identify the 
person's face due to their head blocking the sun light from hitting their 
face. That's why the shadow from their face is a tad bit off, but not very 
noticeable at all. So it makes no sense what so ever for an idiot (which 
I'm referring to those who are against Christ a.k.a. anti-Christ and 
against God the Father in heaven) like those in the media to pay so close 
attention to very small details such as the position of the shadow 
appearance on the person's face when really, it's not that apparent for 
this to even be controversial. The only reason why the media would argue 
about something so stupid such as details from the video is because they 
are trying to hide the truth from the audience by deceiving them due to a 
fact that they are afraid of the truth.
Second of all, with regard to canceling out unwanted audio sounds (such as 
air or wind) from a video, It's called removing hiss and hum sounds from 
the video audio. It is possible to edit out/remove harsh wind sounds 
completely from a audio if the quality of the built-in mic from the 
camcorder is HD. Being in the desert, most times lacks wind, so 
editing/removing out light wind sounds from a video wouldn't be all that 
difficult. Most movie producers do this in order to add sound effects to a 
movie sequence.
Last of all, it's impossible for the Isis' beheading video to be done on a 
green screen since green screen don't/won't allow background shadows such 
as dark shadows or bright flares when editing out a green screen background 
in order to place a background scene. If a dark shadow appears on green 
screen when editing out the green screen from a video, parts of the 
person's shadow such as the shadow from their face will be cut off (which 
will crop the person's face off) if the editor was to remove the background 
shadows behind the person from the green screen. When doing a green screen, 
lighting has to be all balanced out perfectly to be able to crop out the 
green screen from the video perfectly as well to be able to store in the 
background scene to the video. If you watch the beheading video of the two 
Japanese men being beheaded, their dark shadow figure from behind them 
becomes visible/is apparent from the ground in the Isis' video, so that 
should tell you that it's not done from a green screen.

I took video production in college back in the day, so I know because I've 
learn about certain techniques when it comes to editing videos.

If you don't believe me, just look up green screen tutorials on the 
internet or something.
